    "summary": "Croesus of Lydia (r. c. 560–547 BC) was the last king of the Lydian Mermnad dynasty — legendary throughout the ancient world for his wealth (hence 'rich as Croesus') derived from the electrum-rich Pactolus River and the sophisticated trading economy of western Anatolia. His downfall at the hands of [[event:1911|Cyrus the Great]] became one of antiquity's most celebrated cautionary tales about the limits of human prosperity and the danger of misreading oracles.\n\nCroesus made lavish donations to all the major Greek oracular sanctuaries, particularly Delphi, and asked whether he should attack Persia. The Delphian oracle told him that 'if Croesus crosses the Halys River, a great empire will be destroyed.' He crossed — and his own empire was destroyed. Defeated by Cyrus in 547 BC, Croesus was about to be burned alive when, according to Herodotus, he called out the name of Solon (the Athenian lawgiver who had warned him that no man should be called happy before his death). Cyrus, intrigued, spared him. The story of Croesus and Solon — wealth and wisdom, fortune and its reversal — became the opening moral paradigm of Herodotus's Histories and one of the defining stories of Greek moral thought. Croesus's reign also saw the first coinage in gold (as opposed to electrum) issued as currency.",
    "wikipedia_url": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Croesus",
